Keylogging records what you type—passwords, messages, even deleted text—without you noticing. It can be done through software hidden in apps or via compromised keyboards or USB devices. Some malware even sends logs remotely. This bypasses encryption since it captures input before it’s protected. Often used in surveillance, data theft, or spying. Anti-virus tools may miss it. Terms like input capture, hardware keylogger, spyware, screenlogger, and keystroke injection help uncover more. Preventing this starts by isolating devices and minimizing trusted input paths—not just encrypting data after it’s already exposed.